Come on!

5
00:01:20,327 --> 00:01:22,261
<i>Come on!</i>

6
00:01:25,098 --> 00:01:27,532
<i>[ Dog Barking ]</i>

7
00:01:30,470 --> 00:01:32,404
Stay, Bo-Jay.

8
00:01:59,166 --> 00:02:01,031
Hey, Mr. Higgins.

9
00:02:01,101 --> 00:02:04,036
<i>You boys see somethin'</i>
<i>come down around here</i>
<i>about ten minutes ago?</i>

10
00:02:04,104 --> 00:02:07,039
- Yeah, it's back in
the woods, in the clearing.
- It's really incredible.

11
00:02:07,107 --> 00:02:10,042
Come on, you have to
come see it.

12
00:02:17,350 --> 00:02:19,284
It's just through here.

13
00:03:36,963 --> 00:03:40,899
<i>[ Helicopter Blades Whirring ]</i>

14
00:04:09,195 --> 00:04:12,130
- <i>Sam, great to see you.</i>
<i>How you been?</i>
-Ja<i>rv</i>is, good to see you.

15
00:04:12,198 --> 00:04:15,656
- This is Doctor Sefton.
- Mary. Hi.

16
00:04:15,735 --> 00:04:17,965
Sam. Hi.

17
00:04:21,708 --> 00:04:25,144
- What the hell's he doing here?
- <i>[Jarvis ]</i>
<i>This is important, Sam.</i>

18
00:04:27,581 --> 00:04:29,515
Sorry about the short notice.

19
00:04:29,583 --> 00:04:31,642
- No problem.
- They have their I.D.s?

20
00:04:34,955 --> 00:04:36,980
So I'm a Cavanaugh now.

21
00:04:37,057 --> 00:04:40,891
We're tourists. If anyone asks,
I'm Charles Cavanaugh.

22
00:04:40,961 --> 00:04:42,792
<i>Dr. Sefton is your sister.</i>

23
00:04:42,862 --> 00:04:46,798
- My sister?
- Of whom you are extremely fond,

24
00:04:46,866 --> 00:04:49,801
in a clean-cut, healthy,
all-American sort of way.

25
00:04:49,869 --> 00:04:52,303
So where's my sister been all my life?

26
00:04:52,372 --> 00:04:55,307
<i>Dr. Sefton is on loan to us</i> f<i>rom NASA.</i>

27
00:04:56,409 --> 00:04:58,843
Ja<i>rv</i>is, get the trunk for me, will ya?

28
00:04:58,912 --> 00:05:02,643
- Since when did the Office
start drafting civilians?
- All you need to know for now...

29
00:05:02,716 --> 00:05:06,652
is that, in the scheme
of things, she is much more
valuable to us than you are.

30
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:10,656
- And I take it
you're as valuable as ever.
- Naturally.

31
00:05:12,225 --> 00:05:15,661
So, if the two of you are being
shot at, which bullet do I take?

32
00:05:15,729 --> 00:05:18,163
You must try for both, of course.

33
00:05:18,231 --> 00:05:20,165
<i>[ Engine Starts ]</i>

34
00:05:33,913 --> 00:05:37,349
So tell me, Charles, what's so important
to drag you out of your office...

35
00:05:37,417 --> 00:05:39,647
and into the field?

36
00:05:39,719 --> 00:05:44,179
Something unusual was reported
entering our atmosphere last night.

37
00:05:44,257 --> 00:05:47,522
One of our Keyhole satellites
picked this up.

38
00:05:51,431 --> 00:05:53,365
You wanna give me a hint?

39
00:05:53,433 --> 00:05:56,698
See the little blur in
the upper left hand corner?

40
00:05:56,770 --> 00:05:59,068
- Yeah.
- The analysts speculate...

41
00:05:59,139 --> 00:06:02,233
that that's where the U.F.O.
may have landed.

42
00:06:02,308 --> 00:06:04,139
That's all we have?

43
00:06:04,210 --> 00:06:08,579
<i>We immediately sent in</i>
<i>two agents</i>.'<i>Dietman and Truly.</i>

44
00:06:08,648 --> 00:06:12,584
They have failed to report back,
and we have not been able
to contact them.

45
00:06:15,221 --> 00:06:17,155
Peripheral reports?

46
00:06:17,223 --> 00:06:19,157
Well, the usual ground sightings.

47
00:06:19,225 --> 00:06:21,159
Reports of a landing.

48
00:06:21,227 --> 00:06:25,220
And then a local TV station sent in
a mobile unit to do a spot-cast.

49
00:06:25,298 --> 00:06:29,200
And they reported that,
indeed, a U.F.O. had landed.

50
00:06:29,269 --> 00:06:32,204
An hour later they changed their tune.

51
00:06:32,272 --> 00:06:35,799
Claimed that it was a hoax,
a fraud perpetrated by
a couple of farm boys...

52
00:06:35,875 --> 00:06:37,809
who had built this... spaceship.

53
00:06:37,877 --> 00:06:40,402
Nice sign.

54
00:06:46,352 --> 00:06:48,786
<i>[ Children Talking Excitedly ]</i>

55
00:07:00,066 --> 00:07:04,162
- <i>[ Boy ]</i>
<i>Olly olly oxen</i> f<i>ree!</i>
- <i>[ Girl ] That's not</i> f<i>air!</i>

56
00:07:04,237 --> 00:07:06,171
<i>[ Children Talking, Yelling ]</i>

57
00:07:06,239 --> 00:07:09,174
- You go ahead, I'll catch up.
- Okay.

58
00:07:09,242 --> 00:07:12,336
So tell me, Mary,
what exactly do you do for NASA?

59
00:07:12,412 --> 00:07:14,437
My specialty's exobiology.

60
00:07:14,514 --> 00:07:16,573
- Exobiology?
- Mm-hmm.

61
00:07:16,649 --> 00:07:20,278
It's a study of what
alien life forms might be like.

62
00:07:20,353 --> 00:07:23,288
- You actually make a living at that?
- Mmm.

63
00:07:23,356 --> 00:07:25,790
Seems like it'd be mostly guesswork.

64
00:07:25,859 --> 00:07:29,795
We had a joke in school that
ours was the only science that
didn't have a subject matter.

65
00:07:29,863 --> 00:07:32,798
- Huh.
- So you people are with the Office
of Scientific Intelligence?

66
00:07:32,866 --> 00:07:34,800
- Is that right?
- Yeah.

67
00:07:34,868 --> 00:07:38,304
- 'Til two days ago,
I hadn't even heard of it.
- No, you wouldn't have.

68
00:07:38,371 --> 00:07:40,305
Our existence isn't public knowledge.

69
00:07:40,373 --> 00:07:42,568
Eisenhower started O-SCI back in '59.

70
00:07:42,642 --> 00:07:45,076
Technically, we're
an offshoot of the C.I.A.,

71
00:07:45,145 --> 00:07:48,137
but the old man runs it
like his own private dictatorship.

72
00:07:48,214 --> 00:07:51,809
- Pay for this, will you, Sam?
- Sure, Charles.

73
00:07:51,885 --> 00:07:54,945
Three for the, uh, flying saucer.

74
00:08:04,964 --> 00:08:07,626
What do you hear, Sam?

75
00:08:07,700 --> 00:08:10,430
- No birds.
- Hmm.

76
00:08:10,503 --> 00:08:12,630
Right.

77
00:08:12,705 --> 00:08:14,639
No birds.

78
00:08:20,180 --> 00:08:25,208
- <i>Why spend all your money</i>--
- <i>He's old enough to make</i>
<i>his own decisions.</i>

79
00:08:36,696 --> 00:08:39,631
<i>[ Man ] Yeah, hold this.</i>
<i>Straight enough?</i>

80
00:08:39,699 --> 00:08:42,566
[ People Talking ]

81
00:08:43,803 --> 00:08:46,271
- [ Boy ] Be right with ya!
- [ Woman ] Okay!

82
00:08:46,339 --> 00:08:48,773
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>We've traveled a long way.</i>

83
00:08:48,842 --> 00:08:52,539
- <i>Yeah,yeah, there you go.</i>
- <i>[ Woman ] A long way.</i>

84
00:08:57,217 --> 00:09:00,550
Care to see inside, sir?
Only a buck more.

85
00:09:00,620 --> 00:09:02,781
Well, that's a bargain, isn't it?

86
00:09:02,856 --> 00:09:06,849
- <i>Let's have a look, shall we?</i>
- Sure. Hi.

87
00:09:07,927 --> 00:09:11,158
Let's see. Three dollars.

88
00:09:11,231 --> 00:09:12,892
There you go.

89
00:09:14,934 --> 00:09:17,994
<i>[ Sam ] So, how much</i>
<i>have you made so</i> f<i>ar?</i>

90
00:09:18,071 --> 00:09:20,335
About three hundred and twenty.

91
00:09:22,876 --> 00:09:24,810
I'll go first.

92
00:09:40,593 --> 00:09:42,527
Thanks.

93
00:09:42,595 --> 00:09:45,029
Could you help me here? Thanks.

94
00:09:51,437 --> 00:09:53,132
Thank you.

95
00:09:59,445 --> 00:10:02,380
<i>Let's go, lady.</i>
<i>I'm tryin'to run a business here.</i>

96
00:10:02,448 --> 00:10:04,882
<i>Don't risk it, Mary.</i>
<i>It doesn't look sa</i>f<i>e.</i>

97
00:10:04,951 --> 00:10:07,886
Of course it is. We've been takin'
people through all day.

98
00:10:07,954 --> 00:10:11,390
- Well, she balked at the
Pirates of the Caribbean, so--
- Come on.

99
00:10:11,457 --> 00:10:14,949
<i>You know what? Keep the money, guys.</i>
<i>We're running late.</i>

100
00:10:15,028 --> 00:10:17,496
Come on, Mary.

101
00:10:17,563 --> 00:10:19,997
Come on. Thanks, guys.

102
00:10:32,278 --> 00:10:35,714
- Well, Charles?
- Wait a minute, wait a minute.

103
00:10:35,782 --> 00:10:37,716
- Mary?
- I couldn't see anything down there,

104
00:10:37,784 --> 00:10:40,719
but there was definitely
something strange going on.

105
00:10:40,787 --> 00:10:45,520
- Look, what about the burn marks?
- The burn marks were real.

106
00:10:45,591 --> 00:10:49,254
Something landed there.
Something landed there,
but not that thing.

107
00:10:49,329 --> 00:10:51,763
So why that thing, hmm?
Why the cover-up?

108
00:10:51,831 --> 00:10:55,267
- Go on, Mary.
- There was something odd
about those boys.

109
00:10:55,335 --> 00:10:57,769
Same with the man at the gate
and the one in the woods.

110
00:10:57,837 --> 00:10:59,771
What, precisely?

111
00:10:59,839 --> 00:11:03,036
All right, look, I know this
doesn't necessarily qualify
as scientific evidence,

112
00:11:03,109 --> 00:11:06,545
but a woman is used to
a certain response from men
when we meet them:

113
00:11:06,612 --> 00:11:10,548
and from those boys,
I didn't even get the automatic--

114
00:11:10,616 --> 00:11:13,710
Like when I was
introduced to Sam, he did this.

115
00:11:15,288 --> 00:11:17,222
I did not do that.

116
00:11:17,290 --> 00:11:20,225
Based on what I was doing
with my blouse,

117
00:11:20,293 --> 00:11:23,228
they should've tried
to look down my top, something.

118
00:11:23,296 --> 00:11:26,231
- They wouldn't have
had to try very hard.
- Sam.

119
00:11:26,299 --> 00:11:30,736
We're going to go to
the TV station that broadcast
those conflicting reports.

120
00:11:30,803 --> 00:11:34,739
Try something,
and let me know if you get
the same reaction, all right?

121
00:11:34,807 --> 00:11:36,741
- Yes, sir.
- Let's go.

122
00:11:38,277 --> 00:11:41,940
- Did I really do that
when we first met?
- You're still doing it.

123
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:02,734
Ja<i>rv</i>is, stay by the car.

124
00:12:02,802 --> 00:12:06,238
All right, I'll keep it up there.
I'll be waiting for you.

125
00:12:06,305 --> 00:12:08,739
<i>[ Engine Starts ]</i>

126
00:12:10,276 --> 00:12:12,801
That's fine.

127
00:12:14,714 --> 00:12:19,174
The F.C.C. does not take
misrepresentation lightly, Mr. Barnes.

128
00:12:19,252 --> 00:12:21,186
[ Siren Blares ]

129
00:12:21,254 --> 00:12:24,746
<i>We made an explanation</i>
<i>over the air, Mr. Cavanaugh.</i>
<i>What else do you want?</i>

130
00:12:24,824 --> 00:12:28,191
<i>We</i> f<i>ell victim to a practical joke.</i>

131
00:12:28,261 --> 00:12:31,594
<i>It was a... mistake.</i>
<i>We're only human, after all.</i>

132
00:12:36,569 --> 00:12:38,696
Damn. Can I borrow your pen?

133
00:12:48,781 --> 00:12:50,976
Well, I've seen the site,

134
00:12:51,050 --> 00:12:54,577
<i>and I find it difficult to imagine</i>
<i>that a couple o</i>f f<i>arm boys...</i>

135
00:12:54,654 --> 00:12:58,181
could've pulled off
a hoax like that on their own.

136
00:12:58,257 --> 00:13:01,226
Are you implying that
my station was in on it?

137
00:13:02,728 --> 00:13:04,719
Be realistic.

138
00:13:05,631 --> 00:13:08,361
- Hold it!
- Uhh!

139
00:13:15,775 --> 00:13:18,710
- [ Squishing Sound ]
- He's still moving.

140
00:13:24,250 --> 00:13:27,310
- Oh, my God.
- Well, well, well.

141
00:13:27,386 --> 00:13:30,321
- What the hell is that?
- <i>Our visitor, I presume.</i>

142
00:13:30,389 --> 00:13:33,517
<i>Care</i>f<i>ul.</i>

143
00:13:33,593 --> 00:13:37,029
<i>[ Hissing ]</i>

144
00:13:56,282 --> 00:13:58,546
[ Grunting ]

145
00:13:58,618 --> 00:14:01,553
No, Sam! I want to take it back.

146
00:14:01,621 --> 00:14:04,055
Give me that case.

147
00:14:08,027 --> 00:14:11,190
[ Squealing ]

148
00:14:18,604 --> 00:14:22,233
Thank you for your cooperation,
Mr. Barnes.

149
00:14:22,308 --> 00:14:26,904
We will be in touch with you
just as soon as I have
completed the investigation.

150
00:14:30,983 --> 00:14:32,917
They're on their way right now.

151
00:14:32,985 --> 00:14:35,419
[ Reporters' Voices On Tape ]

152
00:14:35,488 --> 00:14:37,422
Let's go, Sam.

153
00:14:49,001 --> 00:14:52,596
- [ Grunts ]
- Oh. Sorry.

154
00:14:53,673 --> 00:14:55,607
- <i>Zoom in, one.</i>
- This way.

155
00:14:55,675 --> 00:14:58,610
<i>Camera three, pull out.</i>
<i>What are these people doing</i>--

156
00:14:58,678 --> 00:15:01,738
<i>Billy, they're coming through.</i>
<i>Stop them, Billy.</i>

157
00:15:01,814 --> 00:15:05,272
<i>[ Anchorman ] Let's start</i>
<i>with what you should do in an emergency.</i>

158
00:15:05,351 --> 00:15:08,787
If you can stay calm, those around you
will react calmer,

159
00:15:08,854 --> 00:15:10,788
especially if you have children.

160
00:15:10,856 --> 00:15:13,791
Once you are calm, then you can put
a plan into place.

161
00:15:16,028 --> 00:15:18,861
Can I see some I.D., please, sir?

162
00:15:18,931 --> 00:15:21,866
Sam, you drive.
Ja<i>rv</i>is, get in the car!

163
00:15:21,934 --> 00:15:23,868
Get away from the car, Officer.

164
00:15:25,004 --> 00:15:27,302
[ Grunting ]

165
00:15:28,708 --> 00:15:30,369
Get in the car.

166
00:15:34,914 --> 00:15:37,644
[ Tires Screeching ]

167
00:15:39,919 --> 00:15:42,387
- <i>He's on the car!</i>
- [ Screams ]

168
00:15:42,455 --> 00:15:44,286
- Get off!.
- [ Groans ]

169
00:15:48,194 --> 00:15:50,526
- [ Screams ]
- Get off!.

170
00:15:50,596 --> 00:15:53,064
- Get him off!.
- [ Grunting ]

171
00:15:54,133 --> 00:15:56,397
- Whoa!
- [ Tires Screeching ]

172
00:15:56,469 --> 00:15:59,495
[ Horn Honking ]

173
00:15:59,572 --> 00:16:02,541
- Sam, get him off!.
- [ Officer Screams ]

174
00:16:09,548 --> 00:16:11,914
There they are!

175
00:16:13,185 --> 00:16:16,052
- Sam!
-<i>[ Tires Screeching ]</i>

176
00:16:16,122 --> 00:16:19,148
[ Boy Yelling ]

177
00:16:19,225 --> 00:16:22,592
<i>It's the kid</i> f<i>rom the spaceship!</i>
<i>Get him off the car!</i>

178
00:16:22,662 --> 00:16:25,222
-<i>[ Sam ]Jarvis!</i>
-<i>[ Mary ]Jarvis! Help him!</i>

179
00:16:25,298 --> 00:16:28,199
[ Horn Honking,
Tires Screeching ]

180
00:16:38,844 --> 00:16:41,039
Oh, my God!

181
00:16:41,113 --> 00:16:43,707
Sam, are you all right?

182
00:16:43,783 --> 00:16:45,717
- Yeah, I'm all right.
- Good.

183
00:17:01,734 --> 00:17:03,668
<i>[ Andrew ] Make sure</i>
<i>Langley understands...</i>

184
00:17:03,736 --> 00:17:06,671
<i>that it is crucial</i>
<i>that we stop this be</i>f<i>ore</i>
<i>it can spread any</i> f<i>urther.</i>

185
00:17:06,739 --> 00:17:10,106
I want that town
sealed up completely.

186
00:17:10,176 --> 00:17:12,110
Put up a perimeter, roadblocks--

187
00:17:12,178 --> 00:17:15,147
You can't use local police
because they have been compromised.

188
00:17:15,214 --> 00:17:18,615
<i>Right? Now, the troops</i>
<i>that you do send in...</i>

189
00:17:18,684 --> 00:17:21,619
<i>should be ordered to put up a challenge</i>
<i>and respond at 1 00 yards,</i>

190
00:17:21,687 --> 00:17:25,487
<i>and put a bullet through anyone</i>
<i>who comes closer than 50 yards.</i>

191
00:17:25,558 --> 00:17:28,823
Now, get Holland to take
a hazard response team...

192
00:17:28,894 --> 00:17:31,328
and investigate the landing site.

193
00:17:31,397 --> 00:17:33,331
- <i>There is no time to waste.</i>
- Mary.

194
00:17:33,399 --> 00:17:35,333
- Thanks.
- Sure.

195
00:17:35,401 --> 00:17:39,838
<i>They should exercise</i>
<i>extreme caution, but I</i>
<i>want to know everything.</i>

196
00:17:39,905 --> 00:17:44,205
- Wasn't supposed to happen like this.
- What wasn't?

197
00:17:44,276 --> 00:17:47,211
First contact.

198
00:17:47,279 --> 00:17:49,713
- What'd you expect, E.T.?
- [ Laughs ]

199
00:17:49,782 --> 00:17:52,307
No, but it would've been nice.

200
00:17:52,385 --> 00:17:54,410
I never really liked
that little troll.

201
00:17:54,487 --> 00:17:58,253
Look. He's in his element now.
He's only really happy during a crisis.

202
00:17:58,324 --> 00:18:01,487
Yeah. Alive.
[ Chuckles ]

203
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:05,155
A little tense between you two, huh?

204
00:18:05,231 --> 00:18:07,426
Yeah, well, he's my father.

205
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:09,434
<i>[ Thumping ]</i>

206
00:18:09,502 --> 00:18:11,993
- [ Thumping Continues ]
- <i>[ Hissing ]</i>

207
00:18:45,704 --> 00:18:49,640
Wow. This is incredible.
[ Laughing ]

208
00:18:49,708 --> 00:18:51,608
- Graves.
- Quite incredible.

209
00:18:51,677 --> 00:18:54,612
There will be plenty of time
for amazement later.

210
00:18:54,680 --> 00:18:57,615
<i>Right now I urgently need</i> f<i>acts.</i>

211
00:18:57,683 --> 00:18:59,844
Okay, here's one: it's dead.

212
00:18:59,919 --> 00:19:01,784
-<i>Are you sure?</i>
- Huh?

213
00:19:01,854 --> 00:19:05,085
No, uh, body heat,
no electrical activity, and no movement.

214
00:19:05,157 --> 00:19:09,093
My guess is, if we vented the chamber,
it'd be pretty ripe in there.

215
00:19:09,161 --> 00:19:12,096
We gave it quite a jolt
of electrical current.

216
00:19:12,164 --> 00:19:15,759
Probably vascular collapse,
although most parasites,
when they're separated--

217
00:19:15,835 --> 00:19:18,770
Dr. Sefton will define what we're
dealing with here.

218
00:19:18,838 --> 00:19:21,773
All right, how do you
wanna handle this?

219
00:19:21,841 --> 00:19:24,776
Well, we need to know how the creature
is able to interface...

